<p class="article__lede">
About 60% of American adults do not have a will. Of the 40% who do, more than half wrote it over ten years ago — back when their children were younger, their assets were smaller, the estate-tax thresholds were different, and the people they named as executors or beneficiaries were sometimes not yet divorced, deceased, or estranged from them. The numbers come from successive surveys by Caring.com, AARP, and Gallup. They have not improved in twenty years. They have, in some categories, gotten worse.
</p>

<p>
The reason this matters is not the will itself. The will is the document everyone has heard of, and the one most people are quietly ashamed of not having. It is also, in most family situations, the third- or fourth-most-important document on the list. The single most important document — the one that decides what happens to you and your family if you are alive but unable to make decisions — is one that almost nobody has heard of by name.
</p>

<p>
This article is the cornerstone of the Legal pillar at AfterChildren. We are going to tell you, in order, the five documents every adult over the age of 55 needs in place. For each one, we are going to tell you what happens to you and your family if you do not have it, what it costs to create, where to create it, and how often it needs to be reviewed. There are no surprises in this list. There is no special insight. The work has been documented by estate-planning attorneys for forty years. The barrier has never been complexity. The barrier has been that the conversation is uncomfortable and the deadline is invisible, so nobody does it, until somebody is in an emergency room and somebody else cannot make the decision that has to be made in the next twenty minutes.
</p>

<h2>The five, in order of operational urgency</h2>

<p>
We are going to list these in the order that matters operationally, not in the order they are usually presented in. Most checklists put the will first, because the will is famous. We are putting it third, because the will only matters after you are dead. The first two documents on this list matter while you are still alive but no longer able to handle your own affairs — which is the scenario that occurs, for most parents, years before death, and which is the scenario almost nobody plans for.
</p>

<ol class="article__five">
  <li><strong>Durable Power of Attorney for Finances.</strong> Names who can manage your money if you cannot.</li>
  <li><strong>Healthcare Directive (Living Will) + HIPAA Authorization.</strong> Names who can make medical decisions, what you want done, and who is permitted to receive your medical information.</li>
  <li><strong>Last Will and Testament.</strong> Distributes your assets after your death and names a guardian for any dependents.</li>
  <li><strong>Revocable Living Trust</strong> (for many but not all families). Sidesteps probate and keeps your estate private after your death.</li>
  <li><strong>Beneficiary Designations Review.</strong> The silent document that overrides everything above on your retirement accounts and life insurance.</li>
</ol>

<p>
Each one is examined below. Each one has a concrete cost, a concrete consequence of not having it, and a concrete place to create it. If you read nothing else on this site, read the five sections that follow and complete the five tasks. The total time, for most families, is one Saturday and roughly $300 to $700.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>1. Durable Power of Attorney for Finances</h2>

<p class="article__lede article__lede--secondary">
The single highest-leverage legal document available to anyone reading this article. If you sign one document this year, sign this one.
</p>

<p>
A Durable Power of Attorney for Finances names a specific person — your "agent" or "attorney-in-fact" — who is legally authorized to make financial decisions on your behalf if you become unable to do so. The word "durable" is doing important work in that sentence. A non-durable Power of Attorney ends the moment you become incapacitated, which is precisely when you need it most. A <em>durable</em> Power of Attorney continues into incapacity. That distinction has filled court dockets for decades.
</p>

<h3>What happens without one</h3>

<p>
You are in the hospital after a stroke. You are alive. You may recover. You may not. While you are unconscious, the mortgage company expects its payment. The car insurance lapses. The electric bill is due. Your spouse — if you have one — can pay the joint bills from joint accounts, but cannot touch the IRA, the brokerage account, or the inherited investment account that is in your name only. Your adult children cannot access anything. Your business, if you own one, cannot operate.
</p>

<p>
The legal solution to this situation, in the absence of a Durable POA, is called a <strong>conservatorship</strong> or <strong>guardianship</strong> proceeding. Your family petitions the local probate court to appoint someone — usually a family member, sometimes a court-appointed stranger — to manage your finances on your behalf. The process takes between two months and a year depending on the state and the complexity. The legal fees range from $3,000 to $15,000. The proceeding is publicly recorded. Court oversight typically continues for the rest of your incapacity, which means annual accountings, court approvals for major decisions, and ongoing legal expense.
</p>

<p>
A Durable Power of Attorney eliminates all of this. The document costs $35 to $150 to create online, takes about thirty minutes to fill out, and needs to be notarized in most states. The single signature is the difference between your family handling your affairs immediately, the day the emergency happens, versus your family hiring a probate attorney and entering a court system designed for situations where nobody trusts anyone.
</p>

<h3>What to specify, briefly</h3>

<p>
The document asks you four practical questions. <strong>Who is your primary agent?</strong> Usually a spouse, sometimes an adult child, occasionally a sibling. The person must be someone you trust with full access to your financial life. <strong>Who is your backup agent</strong>, if the primary cannot serve? <strong>When does the authority become effective</strong> — immediately upon signing (most common, most flexible) or only upon a finding of incapacity by a physician (called a "springing" POA, more restrictive, harder to use in an actual emergency)? And <strong>what powers do you grant</strong> — most states have a comprehensive default list, but you can customize.
</p>

<h3>Where to create one</h3>

<p>
For the roughly 80% of middle-class families with straightforward financial situations — no business ownership, no multi-state property, no special-needs beneficiaries — an online service is genuinely sufficient. <a href="https://trustandwill.com" rel="sponsored noopener" target="_blank">Trust &amp; Will</a> is one of the most credible options, with attorney-reviewed templates customized by state. The Durable POA module is currently bundled into their broader estate-planning packages starting around $159. For the other 20% — business owners, real estate held in multiple states, complex family situations — a local estate-planning attorney is the right call, and the document will be one part of a broader $500 to $2,000 engagement.
</p>

<h3>How often to review</h3>

<p>
Every five years, and immediately after any of the following: the death of the named agent, divorce, a major change in your financial situation, a move to a new state, or an estrangement from a named agent. The document does not expire automatically, but a Durable POA signed in 2008 may not name the right person for 2026.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>2. Healthcare Directive + HIPAA Authorization</h2>

<p class="article__lede article__lede--secondary">
The medical-decision counterpart to the Durable POA. The document that decides what happens to your body when you cannot speak for yourself.
</p>

<p>
A Healthcare Directive — also called a Living Will, Advance Directive, or Healthcare Power of Attorney, depending on the state — does two things. First, it names a <strong>healthcare proxy</strong>: the person legally authorized to make medical decisions on your behalf when you cannot. Second, it documents <strong>your wishes</strong> about specific medical interventions: ventilator support, feeding tubes, resuscitation, pain management, organ donation. It is the document that prevents your family from arguing with each other, in an emergency room, about what you would have wanted.
</p>

<p>
The companion document is a <strong>HIPAA Authorization</strong>. HIPAA — the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act — is the federal law that prevents medical providers from sharing your medical information without your written permission. The default is silence. Without a HIPAA Authorization on file, your spouse and adult children cannot get information from your doctors, cannot call the hospital to check on you, and cannot access your medical records. The Healthcare Directive names the proxy. The HIPAA Authorization gives that proxy — and any other people you list — the legal right to receive information.
</p>

<h3>What happens without one</h3>

<p>
You collapse at a restaurant. By the time paramedics arrive, you are unconscious. You are taken to the nearest emergency room. The hospital does not know who you are or who to call. Eventually they reach your spouse and your adult children. The decision in front of them, in the next three hours, is whether to put you on a ventilator that may or may not be temporary, and what to do if your heart stops during the procedure.
</p>

<p>
Without an Advance Directive, that decision falls to your spouse — assuming your spouse is available and competent — or to your adult children if no spouse exists. They will be making this decision in the worst hours of their lives, without your guidance, often disagreeing with each other, while a hospital staff member with no relationship to your family watches a clock. The "default" decision, in most American hospitals, is maximum intervention: ventilator, feeding tube, full resuscitation. This may or may not be what you would have wanted. The hospital does not know either way.
</p>

<p>
The deeper consequence is rarely discussed. Adult children who make these decisions without guidance often carry the choice for the rest of their lives. A clearly documented Advance Directive removes the guilt from a survivor's lifetime. It is, in real terms, one of the most generous things a parent can do for an adult child. Almost nobody does it.
</p>

<h3>Where to create one</h3>

<p>
Both documents are free in nearly every state. The official Advance Directive form for your state can be downloaded from your state's Department of Health website or from <a href="https://www.caringinfo.org" rel="noopener" target="_blank">CaringInfo.org</a>, a free resource run by the National Hospice and Palliative Care Organization. The HIPAA Authorization form is similarly free and downloadable from most major hospital systems and from the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
</p>

<p>
For families that want a single integrated document set — Advance Directive, Healthcare POA, HIPAA Authorization, all customized to your state and your specific wishes — <a href="https://trustandwill.com" rel="sponsored noopener" target="_blank">Trust &amp; Will</a> bundles all three into their estate-planning packages. The free state forms are operationally fine. The bundled version is faster, more comprehensive, and stored alongside your other estate documents in a single account.
</p>

<h3>Where to keep them</h3>

<p>
A Healthcare Directive does not help anyone if nobody can find it. Three copies: one with your primary care physician, one with your named healthcare proxy, one in your home filed alongside your other estate documents. Some states maintain a registry where you can file your directive for emergency-room access. The American Bar Association maintains <a href="https://www.americanbar.org/groups/law_aging/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">a state-by-state list</a> of these registries. In every state, your named proxy must know that you have named them and where the document is stored.
</p>

<h3>How often to review</h3>

<p>
Every three to five years, and immediately after a major diagnosis, a change in family structure (death, divorce, marriage, estrangement), or a relocation to a different state. Your wishes about specific interventions often shift after age 70 in ways you would not have predicted at 55. The conversation with your proxy is at least as important as the document itself.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>3. Last Will and Testament</h2>

<p class="article__lede article__lede--secondary">
The famous one. Less urgent than the two above. Still non-optional.
</p>

<p>
A Last Will and Testament is the legal document that directs how your assets are distributed after your death, names an <strong>executor</strong> to administer your estate, and — if you have minor dependents — names a <strong>guardian</strong> for those dependents. Most adults over 55 no longer have minor children. The guardianship clause is still relevant if you have minor grandchildren under your care, a disabled adult child, or a dependent parent.
</p>

<h3>What happens without one</h3>

<p>
If you die without a will, you are said to have died "intestate." Your state's intestacy laws — written by your legislature, not by you — distribute your assets according to a default formula. The formula varies by state, but in most states it works approximately as follows. If you are married and all your children are your spouse's children, your spouse inherits everything. If you are married and have children from a previous relationship, your spouse and your children share the estate in fixed proportions (often 1/2 to spouse and 1/2 split among children, or 1/3 to spouse and 2/3 split among children, depending on the state). If you are unmarried with children, your children share equally. If you are unmarried with no children, your assets go to your parents, then your siblings, then more distant relatives.
</p>

<p>
For some families, the default formula produces an outcome the family would have chosen anyway. For most families — and especially for blended families, families with adult children of unequal financial circumstances, families with estranged members, or families where one adult child has provided substantially more caregiving than the others — the default formula produces an outcome the deceased would have considered unjust. The deceased is, by then, not in a position to correct it.
</p>

<p>
Intestate proceedings also tend to be longer, more contested, and more expensive than estates governed by a clear will. The court appoints an administrator. Heirs must be located and notified. Disputes are litigated. A will costing $159 to create can save the estate $5,000 to $25,000 in administration costs and several months of family stress.
</p>

<h3>Where to create one</h3>

<p>
For roughly 70% of families — assets under $3 million, no business ownership, no special-needs dependents, no multi-state property, no second marriages with children from prior relationships — an online will service is sufficient and produces a document of legal quality equivalent to what a $400 attorney would draft. <a href="https://trustandwill.com" rel="sponsored noopener" target="_blank">Trust &amp; Will</a> offers individual will packages starting around $159, attorney-reviewed and state-specific, with optional ongoing updates. <a href="https://www.freewill.com" rel="noopener" target="_blank">FreeWill</a> offers a free basic will (their revenue model is funded by charitable bequests, which is disclosed and reasonable).
</p>

<p>
For the other 30% — blended families, business owners, special-needs beneficiaries, multi-state property, high net worth — a local estate-planning attorney is the right call. Expected cost: $500 to $2,500 for a comprehensive package including will, POA, healthcare directive, and trust (if applicable). The National Academy of Elder Law Attorneys maintains a <a href="https://www.naela.org/findlawyer" rel="noopener" target="_blank">free directory</a> filtered by location and specialty. ACTEC — the American College of Trust and Estate Counsel — maintains a similar directory for higher-net-worth situations.
</p>

<h3>How often to review</h3>

<p>
Every five years, and immediately after: marriage, divorce, death of a named beneficiary or executor, birth of a grandchild you want to include, significant change in net worth, sale or purchase of major real property, or a move to a different state. A will signed ten years ago in a different state, naming a spouse you have since divorced, is worse than no will at all.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>4. Revocable Living Trust (for many but not all families)</h2>

<p class="article__lede article__lede--secondary">
The optional one. For many families, the most efficient estate-planning tool available. For some families, unnecessary.
</p>

<p>
A Revocable Living Trust is a legal entity that holds your assets during your lifetime and distributes them after your death without going through probate court. You — the "grantor" — retain full control over the assets during your lifetime and can dissolve or modify the trust at any time (hence "revocable"). On your death, the assets in the trust pass directly to your named beneficiaries according to the trust's terms, without any court involvement. The trust runs on private contractual law instead of public probate law.
</p>

<h3>When a trust makes sense</h3>

<p>
A trust is the right tool when one or more of the following is true. <strong>You live in a state with expensive or slow probate</strong> — California, Florida, New York, and Texas are the most cited examples, where probate can take 8 to 24 months and cost 3% to 7% of the estate's value. <strong>You own real property in more than one state</strong>, which would otherwise require separate probate proceedings in each state ("ancillary probate"). <strong>You value privacy</strong> — probate proceedings are public record; trust administration is not. <strong>You have a complex family situation</strong> — a blended family, a disabled adult child, a beneficiary in active addiction or financial trouble — where the flexibility of trust-controlled distributions matters. <strong>Your net worth approaches or exceeds the federal estate tax exemption</strong> (currently $13.99 million per individual, scheduled to drop to roughly $7 million in 2026, though that scheduled drop has been postponed before).
</p>

<h3>When a trust is unnecessary</h3>

<p>
A trust is overkill when all of the following are true: you live in a state with simple, fast probate (Pennsylvania, Wisconsin, Indiana, and most of the Midwest); your assets are mostly in retirement accounts, life insurance, and joint accounts that already pass outside probate via beneficiary designations; your family situation is straightforward; and your net worth is well under the federal estate tax exemption. For these families, a properly drafted will plus correct beneficiary designations on retirement accounts (see document #5 below) accomplishes 95% of what a trust would, at 10% of the cost.
</p>

<p>
The estate-planning industry has a financial incentive to recommend trusts to nearly everyone. Trusts cost $1,500 to $4,000 to draft properly versus $400 to $800 for a comprehensive will package. The honest answer for most middle-class families in low-probate states is that the trust is the wrong tool, and the recommendation to use one anyway is a soft form of overselling. The honest answer for families in high-probate states or with complex situations is that the trust is the right tool and is worth every dollar.
</p>

<h3>Where to create one</h3>

<p>
For most families needing a trust, this is the document where the online-vs-attorney calculus shifts toward the attorney. The trust itself is one piece of a coordinated estate plan that also involves retitling your assets into the trust's name — a process called "funding the trust" — which most online services do not handle. An unfunded trust is a $2,000 piece of paper that accomplishes nothing. A local estate-planning attorney handles both the drafting and the funding, typically for $1,500 to $3,500 for a single individual or $2,500 to $5,000 for a couple. <a href="https://trustandwill.com" rel="sponsored noopener" target="_blank">Trust &amp; Will</a> does offer revocable trust packages starting around $499, with the funding instructions left to you — appropriate for the disciplined DIY case but not the typical case.
</p>

<h3>How often to review</h3>

<p>
Same as the will: every five years, and immediately after major life changes. Trusts that are not "funded" with assets retitled into them are the most common estate-planning failure mode. Every five-year review should include verification that all major assets — primary residence, brokerage accounts, valuable personal property — are correctly held in the trust's name.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>5. Beneficiary Designations Review</h2>

<p class="article__lede article__lede--secondary">
The silent document. Almost nobody includes this on the "essential documents" list. It overrides everything above on a meaningful fraction of your assets.
</p>

<p>
Beneficiary designations are the named recipients on your retirement accounts (401(k), 403(b), IRA, Roth IRA), life insurance policies, annuities, and many bank and brokerage accounts ("transfer on death" or "payable on death" designations). These designations are contracts between you and the financial institution holding the asset. They are legally separate from your will. They override your will. If your 401(k) names your ex-spouse from 2007 as the beneficiary, the 401(k) will pay out to your ex-spouse on your death, regardless of what your 2024 will says about distributing your assets to your current spouse.
</p>

<h3>What happens without a review</h3>

<p>
For most adults over 55, a significant portion of total net worth — sometimes 40% to 80% — sits in accounts governed by beneficiary designations rather than by the will. The 401(k) from your previous employer, the IRA you rolled over fifteen years ago, the life insurance policy your employer signed you up for in the 1990s, the savings account you opened when you got married, the small brokerage account from when an aunt died — each of these has a beneficiary or "transfer on death" designation on file. Many of these designations were made decades ago, before subsequent marriages, divorces, births, deaths, or estrangements. They have not been reviewed since.
</p>

<p>
The pattern is consistent across millions of estates. Ex-spouses inherit retirement accounts because the designation was never updated. Adult children who were minors when the designation was made inherit life insurance policies that should have gone to a surviving spouse. Adult children who have since become estranged inherit accounts that the deceased would have left elsewhere. Charities named decades ago — and since dissolved — receive bequests that bounce through legal proceedings before reverting to the estate.
</p>

<p>
This is the one estate-planning task that requires no document creation, no attorney, no cost. It requires one afternoon, a list of every account you own, and the login to each financial institution's website. For each account, you confirm the named primary beneficiary, the named contingent (backup) beneficiary, and update both where appropriate. Most institutions allow the change online in under five minutes per account.
</p>

<h3>The two-step process</h3>

<p>
<strong>Step one: list every account.</strong> Retirement accounts (current and former employer 401(k)s, IRAs, Roth IRAs, SEP-IRAs); life insurance policies (employer-provided and individually purchased); annuities; bank accounts; brokerage accounts; pension plans. Most adults over 55 have between 8 and 25 such accounts. The most common mistake is forgetting about a 401(k) from an employer you left two decades ago — those accounts continue to exist, often with substantial balances, and their beneficiary designations are usually the most out of date.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Step two: log in to each one and confirm the beneficiaries.</strong> Update where the named beneficiary is wrong, dead, estranged, or a former spouse. For each account, name a primary beneficiary and at least one contingent (backup) beneficiary. The contingent matters: if your primary beneficiary predeceases you and you have not named a contingent, the account defaults to your estate, which routes it through probate — exactly the outcome the beneficiary designation was supposed to prevent.
</p>

<h3>Where to track it</h3>

<p>
A simple spreadsheet kept securely — ideally inside a password manager that supports legacy access — is the right tool. <a href="https://1password.com/families" rel="sponsored noopener" target="_blank">1Password Families</a> and <a href="https://bitwarden.com" rel="sponsored noopener" target="_blank">Bitwarden</a> both support legacy access, meaning a designated emergency contact can request access to the vault on your incapacity or death. The vault then contains both the account list and the credentials needed to verify or update the beneficiaries. This single setup solves two problems at once: it documents what your beneficiary designations are, and it gives your family access to the accounts when they need it.
</p>

<h3>How often to review</h3>

<p>
Annually. Every January 1, sit down with the list and confirm nothing has changed. Every five years, log into each account and verify the designations on file match what the spreadsheet says. Most beneficiary errors are caught only after death, when there is no remedy. The annual review is the only protection.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>The Saturday-morning execution plan</h2>

<p>
The five documents above sound like a substantial project. For most middle-class families, the entire set can be completed in one Saturday with a coffee, a quiet morning, and a laptop. The breakdown:
</p>

<ul class="article__plan">
  <li><strong>8:00 to 9:00 a.m. — Account inventory.</strong> List every retirement account, life insurance policy, and major bank account. Print or note current beneficiary designations from each. Most logins will work fine; a few will need password resets.</li>
  <li><strong>9:00 to 11:00 a.m. — Create the four core documents.</strong> Open an account with <a href="https://trustandwill.com" rel="sponsored noopener" target="_blank">Trust &amp; Will</a> (or the alternative of your choice). Complete the will, Durable POA, healthcare directive, and HIPAA authorization. The platform walks you through state-specific options. The total cost is typically $159 to $299 for an individual package, $199 to $399 for a couple.</li>
  <li><strong>11:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. — Print, sign, notarize.</strong> Most documents require notarization. A mobile notary will come to your house for $20 to $50. Your bank, FedEx Office, UPS Store, and most insurance offices offer notary services for $5 to $15 per document.</li>
  <li><strong>12:00 to 1:00 p.m. — Update beneficiary designations.</strong> Log into each retirement account, life insurance policy, and bank account from the morning inventory. Update primary and contingent beneficiaries on each. Most institutions process the change immediately.</li>
  <li><strong>1:00 to 2:00 p.m. — Document storage and notification.</strong> Make three copies of each document. Give one set to your named POA agent and healthcare proxy. File one set in a fireproof safe at home. Upload digital copies to a password manager vault accessible by your designated emergency contact.</li>
</ul>

<p>
Total time: roughly six hours, including breaks. Total cost: $250 to $500 including notarization. Result: the legal infrastructure that protects your spouse, your adult children, and yourself from the worst-case versions of every medical emergency, every estate dispute, and every misdirected inheritance that occurs in families like yours every day.
</p>

<p>
The work is not complicated. It has never been complicated. The barrier is that it is uncomfortable to do and easy to defer, and the deadline — the moment when one of these documents would have prevented a catastrophe — is invisible until it is past. The Saturday morning has been available to most parents for a decade. Most parents have not used it. The five documents on this list, completed at age 60, are the gift to your future self and to your family that nobody talks about giving.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>What we did not cover (and why)</h2>

<p>
This article covers the five documents every adult over 55 needs. It does not cover three related topics that have their own treatments elsewhere on this site or in the pipeline.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Medicaid asset protection</strong> is its own subject. The five documents above are operational essentials. Medicaid planning — using legal structures to protect assets from being spent down on nursing home care, while staying within the five-year lookback rule — is a strategic decision typically made with an elder-law attorney, in your early 60s. Forthcoming article: <em>Medicaid Planning: The Five-Year Lookback Rule Explained</em>.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Digital estate planning</strong> — the question of what happens to your email accounts, photo archives, cryptocurrency, and online subscriptions after your death — is a fast-growing gap that the traditional estate-planning industry has not caught up to. Forthcoming article: <em>The Digital Estate: 40+ Accounts Your Family Cannot Access After You Die</em>.
</p>

<p>
<strong>The inheritance conversation</strong> — the family meeting where you tell your adult children what you have, what you have decided, and why — is its own piece of work, often more emotionally significant than the documents themselves. Forthcoming article: <em>The Inheritance Conversation Nobody Wants to Have (And How to Lead It)</em>.
</p>

<p>
For now: the five documents. This Saturday. The rest of the legal pillar can be built on that foundation, but not before it.
</p>

